This is a common gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request automatically gets its own DI scope.

**In MAUI, there are no automatic scopes.** The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext lives for the entire app lifetime, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.

### Fixes

**Option 1: Use `AddTransient`**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
Each injection gets a fresh instance. Simple, but you lose shared-context-per-unit-of-work.

**Option 2: Create manual scopes** (closer to ASP.NET Core behavior)
```csharp
// Register as scoped (as before)
builder.Services.AddScoped<MyDbContext>();

// In your page/viewmodel, inject the factory:
public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
{
    using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();
    var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
    // db is fresh and disposed when scope ends
}
```

**Option 3: Use `DbContextFactory`** (recommended for MAUI)
```csharp
// Registration
builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();

// Usage
public MyViewModel(IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> factory)
{
    using var db = factory.CreateDbContext();
    // short-lived, no stale tracking
}
```

Option 3 is the EF Core team's recommended pattern for non-HTTP apps like MAUI, Blazor, and WPF.
